The `==` operator will return true if both operands are the same object reference (as well as their values).  It is better to use `.equals()` when comparing string literals for equality because the string literal has its own internal representation that differs from the character array.

```java
// This code works fine
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = new String("Hello");
if(s1 == s2) {
    System.out.println("Same!");
} else {
    System.out.println("Different!");
}

// This does NOT work correctly
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = new String("Hello");
if(s1 == s2) {
    System.out.println("Same!");
} else {
    System.out.println("Different!");
}
```

The reason this doesn't work correctly is that the string literals have different representations internally, which means they're not the same objects despite being the same value.  The `==` operator considers them the same object, but the `.equals()` method compares the *values* of the objects rather than the *objects themselves*.

